<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-10-22T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-10-22T03:00:00-05:00" n="383" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d383">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/4704: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-10-22T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 22,
                                        1924—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 22—9:55
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>398. My 397, October 20, 5 p.m. 1. Following from American consul Canton:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“October 21, 3 p.m. Your October 20, 5 p.m. Three British and two
                                    French river gunboats now in port, also United States ship <hi rend="italic">Helena</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Pampanga</hi>. United States ship <hi rend="italic">Sacramento</hi> at Hongkong. Understand that Russian
                                    cruiser <hi rend="italic">Vorowsky</hi> still at Whampoa.
                                    Japanese consul tells me he will not ask for naval vessel until
                                    necessity evident.</p>
                                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                                <pb facs="0528" n="414" xml:id="pg_414"/>
                                <p>Understand that everything essential in customhouse has already
                                    been transferred to Shameen and that commissioner could carry on
                                    from concession even if Sun seized customs building. Such course
                                    might be preferable to forcible measures by the
                                powers.”</p></quote></p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>